	abstract = {We report the discovery of transient radio emission from the nearby optically discovered tidal disruption event (TDE) ASASSN-14li (distance of 90 Mpc), making it the first typical TDE detected in the radio, and unambiguously pointing to the formation of a non-relativistic outflow with a kinetic energy of ≈(4-10) × 10{\textless}SUP{\textgreater}47{\textless}/SUP{\textgreater} erg, a velocity of ≈12,000-36,000 km s{\textless}SUP{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/SUP{\textgreater}, and a mass of ≈3 × 10{\textless}SUP{\textgreater}-5{\textless}/SUP{\textgreater}-7 × 10{\textless}SUP{\textgreater}-4{\textless}/SUP{\textgreater} M{\textless}SUB{\textgreater}⊙{\textless}/SUB{\textgreater}. We show that the outflow was ejected on 2014 August 11-25, in agreement with an independent estimate of the timing of super-Eddington accretion based on the optical, ultraviolet, and X-ray observations, and that the ejected mass corresponds to about 1\%-10\% of the mass accreted in the super-Eddington phase. The temporal evolution of the radio emission also uncovers the circumnuclear density profile, ρ (R){\textbackslash}propto \{R\}{\textless}SUP{\textgreater}-2.5{\textless}/SUP{\textgreater} on a scale of about 0.01 pc, a scale that cannot be probed via direct measurements even in the nearest supermassive black holes. Our discovery of radio emission from the nearest well-studied TDE to date, with a radio luminosity lower than all previous limits, indicates that non-relativistic outflows are ubiquitous in TDEs, and that future, more sensitive, radio surveys will uncover similar events.},
